### Conditional Rendering

React allows you to conditionally render elements based on state or props using JavaScript operators.

---

### If/Else

```jsx
function Greeting({ isLoggedIn }) {
  if (isLoggedIn) {
    return <h1>Welcome back</h1>;
  }
  return <h1>Please sign in</h1>;
}
```

### Ternary Operator

```jsx
function Status({ isOnline }) {
  return (
    <div>
      User is {isOnline ? 'Online' : 'Offline'}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Logical AND (&&)

```jsx
function Notification({ messages }) {
  return (
    <div>
      {messages.length > 0 && (
        <p>You have {messages.length} unread messages</p>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Pattern Comparison

| Pattern | Use Case |
|---------|----------|
| `if` statement | Multiple branches |
| Ternary `? :` | Toggle between two values |
| `&&` | Render or render nothing |
| `||` | Default fallback value |
| Switch/Map | Multiple conditions |

> **Key Point:** Be careful with `&&` - do not put numbers on the left side. `0 && <Component />` renders `0`, not nothing.

codeExample:
function Dashboard({ user }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{user ? `Welcome, ${user.name}` : 'Please log in'}</h1>
      {user?.role === 'admin' && <AdminPanel />}
      {!user && <LoginButton />}
    </div>
  );
}
